      "title": "Introduction to Perek Mi Shemet: Tumtum and Androgynous Heirs",
      "display_title": "Tumtum/Androgynous Heirs",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks and halakhic categories of ambiguous gender",
          "display_title": "Gender Categories",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinction between Tumtum (safek bechesron yedia) and Androgynous (class safek)",
          "display_title": "Tumtum vs Androgynous",
          "timestamp": "01:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mishnah case: large estate (nechasim merubim) - sons push off Tumtum to daughters",
          "display_title": "Large Estate Case",
          "timestamp": "02:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mishnah case: small estate (nechasim muatin) - daughters push off Tumtum to sons",
          "display_title": "Small Estate Case",
          "timestamp": "03:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Safek dynamics: neither sons nor daughters want Tumtum counted among them",
          "display_title": "Safek Dynamics",
          "timestamp": "03:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Second half of Mishnah: Tumtum and Androgynous cannot claim inheritance (eino notel)",
          "display_title": "Eino Notel Rule",
          "timestamp": "04:13"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Debate between Abaye and Rava: Does Tumtum Receive Any Share?",
      "display_title": "Abaye vs Rava",
      "timestamp": "05:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Abaye's position: Dochin oto ve-ein lo (pushed off and gets nothing)",
          "display_title": "Abaye Position",
          "timestamp": "05:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's objection: Dochin oto ve-yeish lo (doubtful case should yield some claim)",
          "display_title": "Rava Position",
          "timestamp": "05:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's logic: Mamah nafshach - either as son or daughter, should receive something",
          "display_title": "Mamah Nafshach",
          "timestamp": "06:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's response: Doubtful claim cannot obligate giving of another's money",
          "display_title": "Doubtful Claim Problem",
          "timestamp": "06:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Core question: Is child status determined first, then inheritance? Or vice versa?",
          "display_title": "Priority Question",
          "timestamp": "06:47"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabban Shimon ben Gamliel's Position on Kedusha and Tumtum",
      "display_title": "Rabban Shimon",
      "timestamp": "08:05",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Seifa attributed to Rabban Shimon ben Gamliel: Ein kedusha chala aleihem",
          "display_title": "Kedusha Rule",
          "timestamp": "08:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Korban example: if animal is Tumtum or Androgynous, no designation of kedusha",
          "display_title": "Korban Analogy",
          "timestamp": "08:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Interpretation: gender determination must precede designation of offering type",
          "display_title": "Gender First Principle",
          "timestamp": "08:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Fit with Abaye but not with Rava; suggests Rabban Shimon aligns with Abaye",
          "display_title": "Alignment Analysis",
          "timestamp": "09:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Baraita: Tumtum Inherits Like Son, Receives Sustenance Like Daughter",
      "display_title": "Tumtum Baraita",
      "timestamp": "09:25",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Meitivei: Contradictory baraita - Tumtum yoreish keven ve-nizon kebat",
          "display_title": "Contradictory Source",
          "timestamp": "09:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's accommodation: smaller claim in each scenario (male inheritance or female support)",
          "display_title": "Rava's Solution",
          "timestamp": "10:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Bishma le-Rava: baraita fits because Rava gives weaker claim, reconciling texts",
          "display_title": "Reconciliation",
          "timestamp": "10:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ela le-Abaye: problem for Abaye's position that grants nothing",
          "display_title": "Abaye Problem",
          "timestamp": "12:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's reinterpretation: Reaui but not actually receiving (reaui leresh ve-ein lo)",
          "display_title": "Abaye Reframe",
          "timestamp": "14:14"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Preference for Sons vs. Daughters and Birth Order Discussion",
      "display_title": "Son vs Daughter",
      "timestamp": "15:54",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Lemara: is daughter preferable, contradicting Rabbi Yochanan's statement",
          "display_title": "Lemara Question",
          "timestamp": "15:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yochanan quoting Rabbi Shimon bar Yochai: not leaving a son earns God's anger",
          "display_title": "God's Anger",
          "timestamp": "16:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ben adif for inheritance (stronger inheritance); bat adifa for harvacha (gains/provisions)",
          "display_title": "Inheritance vs Gains",
          "timestamp": "18:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Shmuel: Mishnah deals with first child; good sign for future children",
          "display_title": "First Child Sign",
          "timestamp": "20:37"
        },
        {
          "title": "Two explanations of good omen: daughter helps raise siblings OR reduces ayin hara",
          "display_title": "Omen Explanations",
          "timestamp": "21:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Chisda: daughters preferable to him than sons",
          "display_title": "Rav Chisda",
          "timestamp": "22:28"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Tannaim Dispute: Rabbi Meir vs. Rabbi Yehuda on Blessing Daughters",
      "display_title": "Meir vs Yehuda",
      "timestamp": "23:42",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Is our Mishnah like Rabbi Yehuda? References Abraham blessed with bakol",
          "display_title": "Bakol Beriyah",
          "timestamp": "23:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Meir: blessing was NOT having a daughter",
          "display_title": "Meir Position",
          "timestamp": "24:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda: blessing was having a daughter named Bakol",
          "display_title": "Yehuda Position",
          "timestamp": "24:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Second baraita: obligation to feed sons; kal vachomer for daughters (prevent degradation)",
          "display_title": "Feeding Obligation",
          "timestamp": "27:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's kal vachomer preference for daughters in support",
          "display_title": "Yehuda Kal Vachomer",
          "timestamp": "28:58"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Gift on Birth Announcement: Father's Conditional Bequest to Messenger or Child",
      "display_title": "Birth Gift Case",
      "timestamp": "29:03",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Mishnah: 'If my wife bears a son, he shall take 100; if a daughter, 200'",
          "display_title": "Conditional Gift",
          "timestamp": "29:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Initial understanding: gift goes to the child born",
          "display_title": "Child as Recipient",
          "timestamp": "30:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ravina reinterpretation: gift goes to whoever brings the father the news (messenger)",
          "display_title": "Messenger Recipient",
          "timestamp": "33:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Baraita support for messenger reading: 'whoever informs me'",
          "display_title": "Baraita Support",
          "timestamp": "35:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Twins case: if both boy and girl born, messenger gets only 100 (excludes nefel)",
          "display_title": "Twins & Nefel",
          "timestamp": "36:15"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Shchiv Mera Case: Transferring Property to Unborn Child (Ubar)",
      "display_title": "Shchiv Mera & Ubar",
      "timestamp": "37:45",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Dying father designates all property to unborn child in wife's womb",
          "display_title": "Designation Case",
          "timestamp": "37:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna: Mezakeh le-ubar lo kana - cannot transfer ownership to fetus",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna Position",
          "timestamp": "38:06"
        },
        {
          "title": "No yad (hand/agency) to effect kinyan on non-existent person",
          "display_title": "No Yad Problem",
          "timestamp": "39:05"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman's objection via Mishnah: proof that ubar can acquire",
          "display_title": "Rav Nachman",
          "timestamp": "40:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna's defense: don't know who authored our Mishnah",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna Defense",
          "timestamp": "40:45"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Search for Tannaitic Authority: Who Authored the Mishnah?",
      "display_title": "Mishnah Author",
      "timestamp": "42:49",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Testing Rabbi Meir: makneh davar shelo ba'olam (sell non-existent property)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Meir Option",
          "timestamp": "42:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "Objection: Meir allows future property, not property to non-existent person",
          "display_title": "Meir Limitation",
          "timestamp": "43:15"
        },
        {
          "title": "Testing Rabbi Yose: ubar posel ve-eino ma'achil (fetus disqualifies but doesn't benefit)",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yose Option",
          "timestamp": "46:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "Objection: yerusha different from other kinyanim (automatic, not active)",
          "display_title": "Yerusha Distinction",
          "timestamp": "48:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "Testing Rabbi Yochanan ben Beroka: yerusha like matana (gift/bequest)",
          "display_title": "R. Yochanan b. Beroka",
          "timestamp": "49:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Objection: Yochanan's principle applies to existing property, not ubar",
          "display_title": "Beroka Limitation",
          "timestamp": "51:23"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rejected: combining Yochanan with Yose; no independent tannaitic support",
          "display_title": "Combined Option Rejected",
          "timestamp": "51:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Return to Ravina's reading: gift to messenger, not child, resolves apparent contradiction",
          "display_title": "Ravina Escapes",
          "timestamp": "52:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Problem: seifa speaks of yerusha (inheritance), not messenger role",
          "display_title": "Seifa Problem",
          "timestamp": "52:31"
        }
      ]
    }
